{"success": true, "message": "Fetched question.", "data": {"hasAccess": false, "showTimer": true, "showAttemptInsight": true, "playSounds": true, "dontShowCorrectAnswerImmediately": false, "_id": "648b5a6e417cc3fb48d67ef4", "classes": [], "exams": ["615d76b2c52ffa3c944600df"], "subjects": ["615d708dbd4a37c4058ee5a8"], "chapters": ["615d6fed2b295b085ab6eba3"], "topics": [], "concepts": [], "previousYearPapers": [{"_id": "63f499881d196b49d9cd6b13", "title": "JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 1)", "isVisible": true}], "position": 0, "type": "singleCorrect", "level": 3, "approximateTimeRequired": 180, "question": {"text": "&lsquo;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math>&rsquo; polarizing sheets are arranged such that each makes an angle <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math> with the proceeding sheet. An unpolarized light of intensity <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi></math> is incident into this arrangement. The output intensity is found to be <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mi>I</mi><mn>64</mn></mfrac></math> . The value of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math> will be:", "image": null}, "options": [{"id": "IOc3W", "text": "<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math>", "isCorrect": false, "image": null}, {"id": "JEcKB", "text": "<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math>", "isCorrect": true, "image": null}, {"id": "NtZaW", "text": "<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>5</mn></math>", "isCorrect": false, "image": null}, {"id": "9krMl", "text": "<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>", "isCorrect": false, "image": null}], "correctValue": null, "solution": {"text": "<p>When an unpolarized light&nbsp;passes&nbsp;through a polariser, the intensity of the emergent light from the polariser depends on the square of the cosine of the angle between the plane of the polariser and the direction of the incident light.</p><p>The formula to calculate the intensity&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfenced></math>&nbsp;of the emergent light from a polariser which makes an angle&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#952;</mi></math>&nbsp;with the direction of the incident light is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>I</mi><msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>&#952;</mi><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>where,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi></math>&nbsp;is the intensity of the incident light.</p><p>Substitute&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></math>&nbsp;for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#952;</mi></math>&nbsp;into equation (1) to obtain the intensity of the first emergent light.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>I</mi><msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>In a similar manner, the intensity&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfenced></math>&nbsp;of the second emergent light can be written as</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msup><mi>cos</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>45</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mi>I</mi><mn>4</mn></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mi>I</mi><msup><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>Thus, for&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi></math>&nbsp;number of such polarisers, the net intensity&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mfenced></math>&nbsp;of the emergent light can be written as</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>I</mi><mi>n</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mi>I</mi><msup><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi></msup></mfrac><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>Comparing equation (1) with the given expression for the intensity, it can be concluded that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn></math></p>", "image": null}, "videoSolution": {"videoId": "2d2668e11c274baaa8ec0bc8270675ca", "provider": "vdocipher", "thumbnailLight": "https://d1z78r8i505acl.cloudfront.net/poster/aMvsBqCX09af2.480.jpeg", "thumbnailDark": "https://d1z78r8i505acl.cloudfront.net/poster/aMvsBqCX09af2.480.jpeg", "premiumModules": [{"premiumModuleId": "6628114842d540dfcb148ecb", "isFree": false}, {"premiumModuleId": "64c7e8e829737784b294e469", "isFree": false}, {"premiumModuleId": "6788cc0b2dbc1ecacabb7026", "isFree": false}], "des